#use wml::debian::weeklynews::header PUBDATE="2004-06-15" SUMMARY="AMD64, Flyers, Firefox, Documentation, Bootstrapping, Mozilla, Kernel"
# $Id$

<p>Welcome to this year's 24th issue of DWN, the weekly newsletter for the
Debian community.  Tom Adelstein <a
href="http://consultingtimes.com/desktoplinux.html">wrote</a> about GNU/Linux
on the desktop and concluded that it can help enterprises, especially
those short of resources like city governments.</p>

<p><strong>Status of the AMD64 Port.</strong> Chris Cheney <a
href="https://lists.debian.org/debian-devel-announce/2004/06/msg00002.html">\
asserted</a> that "the" AMD64 port of Debian is ready for inclusion in Debian
unstable.  The port is currently at 97&nbsp;% compiled packages with most of
the remaining packages failing to build on other architectures as well.</p>

<p><strong>Updated Debian Flyers.</strong> Michael Banck is <a
href="https://lists.debian.org/debian-events-eu/2004/06/msg00032.html">\
working</a> on updating the <a
href="$(HOME)/events/materials/flyers/general/">general flyer</a> for Debian.
Even though it was written as a general flyer some bits should be updated to
reflect sarge and other releases better.</p>

<p><strong>Packaging Firefox 0.9.</strong> Eric Dorland <a
href="https://lists.debian.org/debian-devel/2004/06/msg00557.html">\
wondered</a> how to handle the next release candidate of Firefox.  Since the
release of sarge will happen soon, he doesn't want it to be left with a
potentially buggy version.  Anthony Towns <a
href="https://lists.debian.org/debian-devel/2004/06/msg00560.html">\
suggested</a> that he uploads the new version of Firefox to
<code>experimental</code> as soon as possible in order to see if it works as
expected.  When it doesn't cause problems, it can be moved to unstable without
much hassle.</p>

<p><strong>License for Documentation?</strong> Matthieu Delahaye <a
href="https://lists.debian.org/debian-legal/2004/06/msg00053.html">\
wondered</a> which license an upstream project should use for their
documentation.  The author wrote a consistent manual for this <a
href="ftp://plg.uwaterloo.ca/pub/uSystem/u++-5.0.ps.gz">software</a> which is
not (yet) compliant with the <a href="$(HOME)/social_contract#guidelines">\
Debian Free Software Guidelines</a> (DFSG).  Walter Landry <a
href="https://lists.debian.org/debian-legal/2004/06/msg00054.html">proposed</a>
to simply stick to the license of the program and don't use a different
license for the documentation.</p>

<p><strong>Cyclic Build Dependencies.</strong> Jeroen van Wolffelaar <a
href="https://lists.debian.org/debian-legal/2004/06/msg00113.html">\
noticed</a> that <a href="http://packages.debian.org/oaklisp">oaklisp</a>
contains a binary file which is used for bootstrapping.  There are at least
half a dozen such <a
href="https://lists.debian.org/debian-legal/2004/06/msg00116.html">loops</a> in
Debian already.  Edmund Grimley Evans <a
href="https://lists.debian.org/debian-legal/2004/06/msg00114.html">assumed</a>
that such cyclic build dependencies are acceptable in Debian.</p>

<p><strong>Mozilla Public License.</strong> Jim Marhaus <a
href="https://lists.debian.org/debian-legal/2004/06/msg00177.html">\
noticed</a> that the new <a href="http://www.mozilla.org/MPL/MPL-1.1.html">\
Mozilla license 1.1</a> is not compliant with the DFSG.  He also phrased a <a
href="https://lists.debian.org/debian-legal/2004/06/msg00221.html">draft
summary</a>.  This mainly affects Mozilla itself, since the other packages
(Firebird, OpenH323, Bugzilla etc.) are not yet relicensed under the new
license.</p>

<p><strong>Debian Kernel Maintenance.</strong> Christoph Hellwig <a
href="https://lists.debian.org/debian-kernel/2004/06/msg00008.html">\
compiled</a> a short todo list for sarge kernels and <a
href="https://lists.debian.org/debian-kernel/2004/06/msg00018.html">\
wondered</a> if more architectures besides i386, powerpc and ia64 are working
on Linux 2.6.  Martin Michlmayr <a
href="https://lists.debian.org/debian-kernel/2004/06/msg00037.html">added</a>
a list of housekeeping issues that have to be dealt with.  William Lee Irwin
II <a href="https://lists.debian.org/debian-kernel/2004/06/msg00104.html">\
contributed</a> the current blacklist of tainted files that need to be
sanitised and/or removed from the kernel.</p>

<p><strong>Security Updates.</strong> You know the drill.  Please make sure
that you update your systems if you have any of these packages installed.</p>

<ul>
<li><a href="$(HOME)/security/2004/dsa-517">cvs</a> --
    Buffer overflow.
<li><a href="$(HOME)/security/2004/dsa-518">kdelibs</a> --
    URI handler vulnerabilities.
<li><a href="$(HOME)/security/2004/dsa-519">cvs</a> --
    Several potential security problems.
</ul>

